---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About | Mod Labs"
  description="Learn how Mod Labs handles console modding and repair, mail-in vs local drop-off, and how customer devices and data are treated."
>
  <section class="hero-gradient border-bottom border-brand py-5">
    <div class="container" data-aos="fade-up">
      <h1 class="display-5 fw-bold section-title mb-2">About Mod Labs</h1>
      <p class="text-muted-brand lead mb-0">
        Mod-first shop with room for repair work when boards need help beyond the usual install.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-5">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="row g-5">
        <div class="col-lg-7" data-aos="fade-up">
          <h2 class="h4 fw-bold mb-3">How we work</h2>
          <p class="text-muted-brand">
            Every build is treated like it’s staying in my own collection: clean flux habits, careful torque on screws, strain relief on flex cables, and the quick smoke test before it goes back to service. Everything is completely personalized and noob friendly, any questions are welcome and progress is relayed consistently.
          </p>
          <h2 class="h4 fw-bold mb-3 mt-4">Doing local drop off only in the Seattle area</h2>
          <p class="text-muted-brand mb-0">
            <strong class="text-light">Local drop-off</strong> for now allows me to provide a quick turnover of a day and sometimes less.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-lg-5" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="100">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-4 bg-brand-surface border border-brand h-100">
            <h2 class="h5 fw-bold mb-3">Devices &amp; data</h2>
            <p class="text-muted-brand small mb-0">
              Customer devices may contain personal data. For Switch and Xbox work, back up anything important before shipping just in case. Storage is not wiped for typical mod installs unless you request it. If a device is unrepairable, you’ll be contacted with next steps.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="pb-5">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="p-4 p-lg-5 rounded-4 bg-brand-surface border border-brand" data-aos="fade-up">
        <div class="row g-4 align-items-start">
          <div class="col-lg-4">
            <h2 class="h4 fw-bold mb-2">About me</h2>
            <p class="text-muted-brand small mb-0">
              Who am I?
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="col-lg-8">
            <p class="text-muted-brand mb-3">
              I’m Al — a hardware modder, electronics tech, and lifelong tinkerer based in Seattle. I’ve spent over nine years repairing, modifying, and bringing hardware back to life, from game consoles and PCs to custom electronics and even cars.
            </p>
            <p class="text-muted-brand mb-3">
              My background blends computer science, IT support, and deep hands-on repair work. I grew up learning mechanical and electrical troubleshooting from my dad, a senior mechanic for buses.
            </p>
            <p class="text-muted-brand mb-0">
              Over the years I’ve developed strong skills in soldering, PCB rework, component-level diagnostics, wiring, and system-level troubleshooting. Whether it’s a simple fix or a full custom mod, I focus on doing the job right, with transparency and craftsmanship you can trust. If it has wires, chips, or moving parts — I can probably fix it, improve it, or make it cooler.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
